**16.8.0preview2.1 / net5.0preview8**: 

**Steps to Reproduce**:

No error or warning is issued if in the constructor property `A` is assigned to itself (in this case it was a typo- silly me!):
```
#nullable enable
    class Foo
    {
        object A { get; set; }
        public Foo(object a)
        {
            A = A;
        }
    }
```
If `A` would be a field instead of an autoproperty, a warning is issued (but not about nullability).

But consider the next example:

```
#nullable enable
    class Foo
    {
        object A;
        object B;

        public Foo(object a)
        {
            A = B;
            B = A;
        }
    }

```

Again no error or warning, even if `A` and `B` are fields!

**Expected Behavior**:

A warning should be issued that an uninitialized member is used.

**Actual Behavior**:

No warning or error.

As per a [blog post](https://devblogs.microsoft.com/dotnet/automatically-find-latent-bugs-in-your-code-with-net-5), .NET 5 introduces new warning message `CS8073`.

The following code from the blog post:

```csharp
public void M(DateTime dateTime)
{
    if (dateTime == null) // warning CS8073
    {
        return;
    }
}
```

will produce the following warning after upgrading Analysis Level to 5 as per the blog post:

> Warning CS8073: The result of the expression is always 'false' since the value of type 'DateTime' is never equal to 'null' of type 'DateTime?'

Personally, I would be quite confused by the part `of type ‘DateTime?’` as there is no `DateTime?` mentioned in the code. As there is nothing else in the sample, I guess that `DateTime?` refer to the `null` check as `null` is a valid value for `DateTime?` but not for `DateTime`.

As such, I suggest to reword the message to replace the part `of type ‘DateTime?’` into a suggestion to either remove the condition or change the type of `dateTime` to `DateTime?`. Alternatively, reword it so it is clear what the ending refers to.

